@node intro "What is this silly program?"

				@{b}@{u}What is this silly program?@{uu}@{ub}

@{i}Lil' Jimmy had never been in a situation like this before... His math teacher had
asked the impossible of him. The project questions lay on the table menacingly, as if they
knew of his fate. He frantically searched through his programs for one that may help him in his
seemingly impossible task...
@{b}But then!@{ub} 
Something had caught his eye on his computer screen, something that he had never noticed before.
Was this the innocent program that could help him in his quest through the jungle of sine's and 
cosine's that sat in front of him on the paper? It was:@{ui}

@{b}@{fg shine}MODULE-GRAPHER!@{fg text}@{ub}

It started off as something that I needed to do for a maths project and then mutated into this
hideous bloated piece of software now taking up space on your Hard Disk. What it does is 
take formulae (trigonometrical ones) and display them in a window (Wow! Exciting!), for which 
you can alter the constants in the @{bg fill}@{" equations " link tech}@{bg background}. It also will draw a kind of fractal which is based
on a particular iterative formula.

Load it up and fiddle!

@endnode

@node req "What you need"

					@{b}@{u}What you need@{uu}@{ub}

There are a couple of basic requirements to even get Module-Grapher up and running. These are:
@{fg fill}
	·Workbench 3.x (due to GadTools and ASL.library usage)
	·The usual Workbench libraries
	·An okay processor (68020+)
	·A Workbench depth of 16+ colours
@{fg text}

Reccommended stuff:
@{fg fill}
	·At least 640x512 display (there's lots of windows!)
	·A decent Workbench depth (ie. more than 16 colours)
@{fg text}

@endnode

@node use "How to use it"

					@{b}@{u}How to use it@{uu}@{ub}

Firstly, if you are reading this section then you must be quite illterate to normal computer
practicies - NEVER READ MANUALS! On the other hand, you could just want to know what everything 
does. 

When you load up the program first, you will be presented with a window called @{bg fill}@{" Control " system "sys:utilities/multiview ctrl_win.iff"}@{bg background}, from
which the Graph window is controlled. If you go up to the menu called "Window", and select
@{bg fill}@{" Graph " system "sys:utilities/multiview grp_win.iff"}@{bg background}, then you will see a largish (depending upon your screen) window appear. Choose the
module you would like to plot from the @{bg fill}@{" Module " system "sys:utilities/multiview mod_gad.iff"}@{bg background} gadget, and change the variables "A", "B" and
"C" to your heart's desire...There are several other gadgets to play with, but these are really 
self-explanatory.
If you select the @{bg fill}@{" Fractal control " system "sys:utilities/multiview frc_ctrl_win.iff"}@{bg background} itm on the menu, you will see another window appear which, once
the "Fractal control" is opened, will control the drawing and ranges of the fractal diagram.
Finally, you can open the @{bg fill}@{" Fractal " system "sys:utilities/multiview frc_win.iff"}@{bg background}window which displays the plots controlled by the "Fractal control".

Simple, really!

For a more technical explanation go @{bg fill}@{" here! " link tech}@{bg background}

@{u}Tooltypes@{uu}	

	(not many so far!)

	REQUESTERS - enable or disable to turn the requesters on or off.


@endnode

