@node err "Error codes"

				@{b}@{u}Error codes@{uu}@{ub}

A description of all the small errors that can take place. None of these should stop the program
from working; they're just annoying!

@{i}Code@{ui}	@{i}Description@{ui}
----	-----------
 0  	Not enough memory to make the program a commodity (don't worry too much ;)
 1  	Can't write to configuration file (envarc:mdlgraph.cfg)
 2  	Can't write to preferences file (you'll end up with defaults instead)
 3  	Can't write to tooltypes
----	----------- 

@endnode
	
@node tech "Ohh...complexish maths..."

					@{b}@{u}Ohh...complexish maths...@{uu}@{ub}

The maths behind this is quite simple (although it doesn't sound like it ;), but if you really 
want to know:

The "fractal convergence diagrams" are produced using what is called an "iterative formula".
First, the computer takes this iterative formula, let's say:

	 			@{b}x -> x^2/(x+c)@{ub} @{i}(derived from sqr(x(x+c))-x)@{ui}

and starts with a c (constant, plotted on the y-axis) value of the smallest y-range, say -40, 
and an x value of the smallest x-range, say -40 again. Then the computer starts going round the 
loop for a c-value of -40, and an x-value of -40 to the biggest x-range, say 40. Once the computer 
has reached x=40, the y increases (-39) and the process starts again. 

Inside the loop done for every value of x (-40 to 40 in our example), it iterates this formula
( x^2/(x+c) ) however many times for the pixel it is testing. The reason for doing this relates
back to so-called "cobweb diagrams" where you plot your starting x-value on a graph of the function
along with a y=x line; and as it iterates, so the line drawn traces it's way up to the curve, and 
then onto the y=x line and onto the curve again etc... This produces the "cobweb" pattern. You then
can tell from the number of times you had to trace the line to the curve and so on, about how
fast the iterative sequence you derived was at converging on the root.

My code not only does that for one line of x values, but for different values of a constant put
in the original equation also. Thus like the Mandlebrot diagrams, this also goes through a 
sequence for each pixel...

@endnode

@node fut "The future of Module-Grapher...and beyond"

					@{b}@{u}The future of Module-Grapher...and beyond@{uu}@{ub}

I have thought of a few things that I need to do with Module-Grapher, but any suggestions would 
be appreciated.
@{fg fill}
	·Better optimisation of graph-drawing and convergence diagram-drawing
	·Do an MUI version (using EFMUILib for those who are interested)
	·Add a possibility of users inputting their own modules for plotting, 
	 and fractal convergence formulae (hence the name "Module-Grapher")
	·Maybe a Newton-Raphson based iterative diagram
	·Umm...your suggestions!
@{fg text}

@endnode

